article.headline: North Carolina State 64, East Carolina 57
article.story: RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) -- Brandon Costner's shooting touch arrived just in time for North Carolina State. Costner scored all 12 of his points in the second half to help the Wolfpack beat East Carolina 64-57 on Thursday night. But none of his points were bigger than two free throws Costner made with 1:37 left in the game. After being fouled putting up a 3-pointer by Jeremy Ingram, Costner missed the first but hit the next two to give the Wolfpack (8-4) the lead for good. Costner was instrumental in the comeback as he hit 3-pointers three separate times to give N.C. State the lead in the final 9:25. "You learn when your opportunities are and when you have a chance to attack, Costner said. "Once I figured that out I just had to exploit them." Ingram, who finished with a season-high 24 points, responded twice with 3-pointers of his own to give the lead back to the Pirates (4-7). But in the end it wasn't enough as those were his only second-half points. "We just have to be more mentally tough down the stretch," Ingram said. "I don't think we panicked. It's just a tough break. They played man (defense) on me in the second half and you know what happened after that." East Carolina's biggest lead of 34-19 came in the first half after Ingram hit a shot in the lane with about three minutes left. N.C. State came back with a 10-2 run to get within seven at the break. East Carolina burned two time-outs in the first five minutes of the second half as N.C. State's Ben McCauley began to take over in the middle. He scored eight of the Wolfpack's first 14 points after the break and finished with 20. "I feel bad for our kids," East Carolina coach Ricky Stokes said. "They played so hard. We have to give N.C. State a lot of credit. They made the necessary plays down the stretch." East Carolina played zone defense most of the game and stymied N.C. State's offense. The Wolfpack shot 41.9 percent (18-of-43) in the game and was outrebounded 34-31. But the Wolfpack dominated at the free-throw line, making 21 of 31 attempts, while the Pirates were only 2-of-9. East Carolina shot 53.6 percent (15-of-28) in the first half but cooled off in the second half, going 9-of-27. The Pirates made five 3-pointers in the first half but only two in the final 20 minutes. "I think the difference in the game was that we started to get patient on offense and turned up the defense," N.C. State coach Sidney Lowe said. East Carolina's bid for its first win in 17 tries against the bigger Wolfpack came up short as the Pirates lost for the sixth straight time this season and N.C. State snapped a two-game losing streak. Trevor Ferguson, who finally joined the Wolfpack's roster two games ago after sitting out the first semester, missed the game with the flu.
